The differential ac Stark shift of a transition containing the ground state and an excited state is the difference between the ac Stark shifts of the 
two states and is given by
\begin{eqnarray}\nonumber
\delta (\Delta E)_{ge} (\omega ) &=&\Delta E_g(\omega)-\Delta E_e (\omega) \\
                      &=&-\frac{1}{2}\left[\alpha_g(\omega)-\alpha_e(\omega)\right]{\cal E}^2 .
\end{eqnarray}  
Here, subscripts `$g$' and `$e$' represent the ground and excited states, respectively. Our aim is to find out the $\omega$ values at which
$\delta (\Delta E)_{ge} (\omega )$ will be zero. 


