For a state of an atomic system having a closed core and a valence electron, dipole polarizabilitiy can be conveniently evaluated by calculating
contributions separately due to the core, core-valence and valence correlations \cite{nandy, jasmeet}. In other words, we can write
\begin{eqnarray}
\alpha_v(\omega)=\alpha_0^{c}(\omega)+\alpha_v^{cv}(\omega)+\alpha_v^{v}(\omega), 
\end{eqnarray}
where $\alpha_0^{c}(\omega)$, $\alpha_v^{cv}(\omega)$ and $\alpha_v^{v}(\omega)$ are the contributions from the core, core-valence and valence 
correlation effects, respectively. The subscript `$0$' in $\alpha_0^{c}(\omega)$ means it is independent of the valence orbital in a state.
